  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Latvia's digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The income requirement is 2.5 times Latvia's minimum wage, approximately €2,857-3,843/month depending on current rates. You must demonstrate this income consistently over 6 months through tax office verification and bank statements.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the OECD requirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Your employer or business must be registered in an OECD member country (38 countries including US, UK, Canada, Australia, most EU countries, Japan, Korea, etc.). If you work primarily for clients in non-OECD countries, you won't qualify for Latvia's DNV.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get permanent residency through Latvia's DNV?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes—this is a unique advantage. Two years of legal residence on Latvia's DNV qualifies you to apply for permanent residence. This makes Latvia one of the few EU countries where a digital nomad visa provides a path to long-term settlement.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Will I pay Latvian taxes on my income?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          It depends on your stay duration. If you stay ≤183 days/year and maintain tax residency elsewhere, you're not a Latvian tax resident and foreign income isn't taxed. If you stay >183 days/year, you become a tax resident and owe progressive income tax (up to 31%) on worldwide income.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How cold are Latvian winters?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Riga winters are cold—average January temperatures around -5°C (23°F), occasionally dropping below -20°C. If you're from a warm climate, this is a significant adjustment. However, Riga's cozy café culture, indoor activities, and hygge-style comfort make winter manageable.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is English widely spoken in Latvia?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          English is widely spoken in Riga, especially among younger people and in business settings. Latvian is the official language, and Russian is also common. You can navigate daily life in English, but learning basic Latvian phrases helps with integration.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

